by the modern interlopers—their lives and experiences, implied by their portraits—threatened the formal closure that had served as a powerful symbolic form of the pact between God and humans. The Embedded Portrait reconstructs this art historical drama from the point of view of the artists rather than the patrons. Following clues left by Vasari, the book assigns a leading role to the painter Giottino, or “little Giotto.” Little-known today but highly regarded in his lifetime, Giottino proposed a new manner of painting that was later realized by Fra Angelico through his own innovative approach to the problem of the embedded portrait.Seeking not to stabilize the artworks but to extend their reach, the interpretations offered in The Embedded Portrait re-create and update the psychic and libidinal energies that gave rise to these works in the first place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBenefactors in art. 0aPortraits, Italian. 0aPortraits, RenaissancezItaly. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh  aAlberti on portraits.  aAllegory of Obedience.  aFlorence.  aGiotto Fra Angelico.  aGiotto de Stefano.  aHistoriography of art history.  aItalian.  aItaly.  aLamentation over the Body of Christ.  aLamentation over the Dead Christ.  aLate medieval.  aMiddle Ages.  aPainting Portrait.  aPatronage.  aPatrons.  aPieta.  aPortraiture Donor.  aRealism.  aReligion.  aRenaissance.  aSacred art.  aSiena.  aart beauty.  aart criticism.  aart history.  acompositional features in art.  aembedded portraits.  afourteenth century art.  aportraits.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691254609?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691254609